snippet.textDisplay:
Fury self-promoted himself into big-time boxing - through always being hilarious in press conferences and KO'ing most his opponents. His interviews on IFL were the only ones to consistently get big views in the early days of the channel - Fury damn near started IFL TV's popularity like Mayweather did 24/7.
His first big-stage event was probably Chisora for the European and the WBO Title - that was almost 10 years ago. Fury could've come back and fought AJ, Ruiz, or Whye, and he would've been getting just as much coverage and respect. Wilder is benefitting from this more than anyone else, because it's him and the PBC (Al Haymon and Shelly Finkel) who so desperately want 50%/50% and EVERYTHING on their terms in the AJ match (e.g. not fighting in the UK, and pick of the judges/refs etc), and they could only get this by fighting Fury beforehand.
snippet.textOriginal:
*Fury self-promoted himself into big-time boxing* - through always being hilarious in press conferences and *KO'ing most his opponents.* His interviews on IFL were the only ones to consistently get big views in the early days of the channel - *Fury damn near started IFL TV's popularity like Mayweather did 24/7.* 
        *His first big-stage event was probably Chisora* for the European and the WBO Title - *that was almost 10 years ago.* Fury could've come back and fought AJ, Ruiz, or Whye, and he would've been getting just as much coverage and respect. Wilder is benefitting from this more than anyone else, because it's him and the PBC (Al Haymon and Shelly Finkel) who so desperately want 50%/50% and EVERYTHING on their terms in the AJ match (e.g. not fighting in the UK, and pick of the judges/refs etc), and *they could only get this by fighting Fury beforehand.*
